\title{Commit Security Scan}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{security}

\tag{scanning}

\tag{vulnerability-detection}

\tag{ci-cd}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Analyze code changes for security vulnerabilities using LLM reasoning and threat model patterns. Use for PR reviews, pre-commit checks, or branch comparisons.}

\subtree{
\title{Commit Security Scan}
\p{Analyze code changes (commits, PRs, diffs) using LLM-powered reasoning to detect security vulnerabilities. This skill reads code directly and applies patterns from the repository's threat model to identify issues across all STRIDE categories.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\ul{
\li{\strong{PR review} - Automated security scan on pull requests}
\li{\strong{Pre-commit check} - Scan staged changes before committing}
\li{\strong{Branch comparison} - Review security of feature branch changes}
\li{\strong{Code review assistance} - Help reviewers spot security issues}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\p{This skill requires:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Threat model} - \code{\startverb .factory/threat-model.md\stopverb} must exist}
\li{\strong{Security config} - \code{\startverb .factory/security-config.json\stopverb} for severity thresholds}
}

\p{\strong{IMPORTANT: If these files don't exist, you MUST generate them first before proceeding with the security scan.}}

\p{To generate the prerequisites:}

\ol{
\li{Tell the user: "The threat model doesn't exist yet. I'll generate it first before scanning."}
\li{Run the \code{\startverb threat-model-generation\stopverb} skill to create both files}
\li{Once complete, continue with the security scan}
}

\p{Do NOT ask the user to run the skill manually - just do it automatically as part of this workflow.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Inputs}
\p{The skill determines what to scan from the user's request:}

\pre{\startverb
| Scan Type         | How to Specify             | Example                                      |
| ----------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| PR                | "Scan PR #123"             | `Scan PR #456 for security vulnerabilities`  |
| Commit range      | "Scan commits X..Y"        | `Scan commits abc123..def456`                |
| Single commit     | "Scan commit X"            | `Scan commit abc123`                         |
| Staged changes    | "Scan staged changes"      | `Scan my staged changes for security issues` |
| Uncommitted       | "Scan uncommitted changes" | `Scan working directory changes`             |
| Branch comparison | "Scan from X to Y"         | `Scan changes from main to feature-branch`   |
| Last N commits    | "Scan last N commits"      | `Scan the last 3 commits`                    |
\stopverb}

\p{If no scope is specified, prompt the user for clarification.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Instructions}
\p{Follow these steps in order:}

\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Verify Prerequisites (Auto-Generate if Missing)}
\p{Try to read these files:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb .factory/threat-model.md\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb .factory/security-config.json\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{If either file is missing or cannot be read:}}

\ol{
\li{Inform the user: "The security threat model doesn't exist yet. I'll generate it first - this may take a minute."}
\li{Invoke the \code{\startverb threat-model-generation\stopverb} skill to analyze the repository and create both files}
\li{Once generation completes, continue with Step 2}
}

\p{This ensures the security scan always has the threat model context it needs for accurate analysis.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Get Changed Files}
\p{Based on the user's request, get the list of changed files and their diffs using git:}

\ul{
\li{For PRs: use \code{\startverb gh pr diff\stopverb}}
\li{For commits/ranges: use \code{\startverb git diff\stopverb} or \code{\startverb git show\stopverb}}
\li{For staged changes: use \code{\startverb git diff --cached\stopverb}}
}

\p{Read the full content of each changed file for context.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Load Threat Model}
\p{Read \code{\startverb .factory/threat-model.md\stopverb} and \code{\startverb .factory/security-config.json\stopverb} to understand:}

\ul{
\li{The system's architecture and trust boundaries}
\li{Known vulnerability patterns for this codebase}
\li{Severity thresholds for findings}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Analyze for Vulnerabilities}
\p{For each changed file, systematically check for STRIDE threats:}

\subtree{
\title{S - Spoofing Identity}
\ul{
\li{Missing or weak authentication checks}
\li{Session handling vulnerabilities}
\li{Token/credential exposure in code}
\li{Insecure cookie settings}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{T - Tampering with Data}
\ul{
\li{\strong{SQL Injection}: String concatenation/interpolation in SQL queries}
\li{\strong{Command Injection}: User input in shell commands, \code{\startverb eval()\stopverb}, \code{\startverb exec()\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{XSS}: Unescaped user input in HTML/templates}
\li{\strong{Mass Assignment}: Blind assignment from request to model}
\li{\strong{Path Traversal}: User input in file paths without validation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{R - Repudiation}
\ul{
\li{Missing audit logging for sensitive operations}
\li{Insufficient error logging}
\li{Log injection vulnerabilities}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{I - Information Disclosure}
\ul{
\li{\strong{IDOR}: Direct object access without ownership verification}
\li{Verbose error messages exposing internals}
\li{Hardcoded secrets, API keys, credentials}
\li{Sensitive data in logs or responses}
\li{Debug endpoints exposed}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{D - Denial of Service}
\ul{
\li{Missing rate limiting on endpoints}
\li{Unbounded resource consumption (file uploads, queries)}
\li{Algorithmic complexity attacks (regex, sorting)}
\li{Missing pagination on list endpoints}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{E - Elevation of Privilege}
\ul{
\li{Missing authorization checks on endpoints}
\li{Role/permission bypass opportunities}
\li{Privilege escalation through parameter manipulation}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 5: Assess Each Finding}
\p{For each potential vulnerability:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Trace data flow}: Follow user input from source to sink}
}

\ul{
\li{Where does the input come from? (request params, body, headers, files)}
\li{Does it pass through validation/sanitization?}
\li{Where does it end up? (database, shell, response, file system)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Check for existing mitigations}:}
}

\ul{
\li{Is there validation elsewhere in the codebase?}
\li{Are there middleware/decorators that protect this code?}
\li{Does the framework provide automatic protection?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Determine severity}:}
}

\ul{
\li{\strong{CRITICAL}: Remote code execution, auth bypass, data breach}
\li{\strong{HIGH}: SQL injection, XSS, IDOR, privilege escalation}
\li{\strong{MEDIUM}: Information disclosure, missing security headers}
\li{\strong{LOW}: Best practice violations, minor issues}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Assess confidence}:}
\li{\strong{HIGH}: Clear vulnerable pattern, direct data flow, no mitigations}
\li{\strong{MEDIUM}: Possible vulnerability, some uncertainty about context}
\li{\strong{LOW}: Suspicious pattern, likely has mitigations we can't see}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 6: Generate Report}
\p{Create \code{\startverb security-findings.json\stopverb} with this structure:}

\pre{\startverb
{
  "scan_id": "scan-YYYY-MM-DD-XXX",
  "scan_date": "<ISO 8601 timestamp>",
  "scan_type": "pr|commit|range|staged|working",
  "commit_range": "<base>..<head>",
  "pr_number": null,
  "threat_model_version": "<from security-config.json>",
  "findings": [
    {
      "id": "VULN-001",
      "severity": "HIGH",
      "stride_category": "Tampering",
      "vulnerability_type": "SQL Injection",
      "cwe": "CWE-89",
      "file": "src/api/users.py",
      "line_range": "45-49",
      "code_context": "<vulnerable code snippet>",
      "analysis": "<explanation of why this is vulnerable>",
      "exploit_scenario": "<how an attacker could exploit this>",
      "threat_model_reference": "Section 5.2 - SQL Injection",
      "existing_mitigations": [],
      "recommended_fix": "<how to fix the vulnerability>",
      "confidence": "HIGH",
      "reasoning": "<why this confidence level>"
    }
  ],
  "summary": {
    "total_findings": 0,
    "by_severity": { "CRITICAL": 0, "HIGH": 0, "MEDIUM": 0, "LOW": 0 },
    "by_stride": {
      "Spoofing": 0,
      "Tampering": 0,
      "Repudiation": 0,
      "InfoDisclosure": 0,
      "DoS": 0,
      "ElevationOfPrivilege": 0
    },
    "files_analyzed": 0
  }
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 7: Report Results}
\ol{
\li{Save findings to \code{\startverb security-findings.json\stopverb}}
\li{Report summary to user (findings count by severity, triggered thresholds)}
\li{Check severity thresholds from \code{\startverb security-config.json\stopverb} and note if any are triggered}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{CWE Reference}
\p{Common CWE mappings for findings:}

\pre{\startverb
| Vulnerability Type       | CWE     |
| ------------------------ | ------- |
| SQL Injection            | CWE-89  |
| Command Injection        | CWE-78  |
| XSS (Reflected)          | CWE-79  |
| XSS (Stored)             | CWE-79  |
| Path Traversal           | CWE-22  |
| IDOR                     | CWE-639 |
| Missing Authentication   | CWE-306 |
| Missing Authorization    | CWE-862 |
| Hardcoded Credentials    | CWE-798 |
| Sensitive Data Exposure  | CWE-200 |
| Mass Assignment          | CWE-915 |
| Open Redirect            | CWE-601 |
| SSRF                     | CWE-918 |
| XXE                      | CWE-611 |
| Insecure Deserialization | CWE-502 |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Invocations}
\p{\strong{Scan a PR:}}

\pre{\startverb
Scan PR #123 for security vulnerabilities
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Scan staged changes before committing:}}

\pre{\startverb
Scan my staged changes for security issues
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Scan a feature branch:}}

\pre{\startverb
Scan changes from main to feature/user-auth for vulnerabilities
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Scan recent commits:}}

\pre{\startverb
Scan the last 5 commits for security issues
\stopverb}
}

